issue.title: [FIX] base: respect 0 margins/spacing overrides for wkhtmltopdf
issue.body:
When constructing the wkhtmltopdf command arguments, the system retrieves values from the `specific_paperformat_args` dictionary using get and checks whether the returned value is falsy.

Because 0 is a falsy value in Python, margin and header spacing values explicitly set to 0 are mistakenly ignored. As a result, the system incorrectly falls back to the default paperformat values instead of honoring the overrides provided in `specific_paperformat_args`.

This commit updates the conditional checks so that values from `specific_paperformat_args` correctly override the paperformat defaults even when the override is 0. This allows users to intentionally remove all margins and spacing defined on the report.

Task-5079740

---

issue.title: Sandbox Bypass Allows Arbitrary File Read and SSRF
issue.body:
a critical sandbox bypass vulnerability exists in paper-muncher. the --sandboxed flag is intended to restrict file and network access, but it is not correctly enforced when a document loads sub-resources.

a malicious HTML file can reference external resources (e.g., ) or internal network endpoints.

the rendering engine fetches these sub-resources using a new, unsandboxed HTTP client, ignoring the user-specified security restrictions.

this allows for arbitrary local file reads and Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF), completely circumventing the sandbox.

comment.body:
Thanks for the report!

Just to clarify: Vaev doesnâ€™t instantiate any HttpClient internally. All
sub-resource loading (images, stylesheets, etc.) is done strictly through the
Http::Client instance provided by Paper-Muncher when creating the DOM Window.

You can see this in _fetchResourcesAsync(), _fetchStylesheetAsync(),
_fetchImageContentAsync(), and fetchDocumentAsync(), all of which take the
existing client by reference.

So there is no second â€œunsandboxedâ€ client being constructed anywhere in Vaev.

There *is* still limited file I/O allowed by the sandbox today, which weâ€™re
already working on tightening, but that is unrelated to the HTTP transport or
client instantiation.

If you have a PoC showing an actual network request bypassing the sandboxed
transport, please share it â€” it would help verify whether this is a real
security issue or a misunderstanding of the code paths.

issue.title: Fails to build with src/vaev-engine/style/specified.cpp:64:5: error: unknown type name 'f16'
issue.body: Now, ```.cutekit/extern/skift-org/karm/src/karm-core/base/base.cpp``` does contain an ```export using``` definition for ```f16```, but it's a) commented out and b) ifdef-gated behind a ```__FLT16_MANT_DIG__``` flag which doesn't appear to be set anywhere and there's no documentation on how to pass defines to cutekit. Not submitting a pull request because simply uncommenting that bit is unlikely to be the desired solution, largely because I don't understand what these what-are-essentially-fancy-typedefs are being used to achieve (in the grand scheme of things, not mechanically), it's either "modern C++ wisdom" that's beyond me or the other way around, but in either case I'm the wrong person to decide what to do with them.

comment.body: Just replace the f16 by a f32, I will fix it later today ;)

issue.title: cutekit fails to pick up latest clang
issue.body:
When trying to build vaev, I got a number of compilation errors that I deduced stemmed from using an older clang. Upon inspection, it became clear cutekit's ```{shell.latest('clang++')}``` was picking up ```clang++-17``` from ```AUR/clang17-bin```

I wasn't able to quickly track down where in cutekit this lives, but removing ```clang17-bin``` solved the problem (moved past that particular error anyway) inasmuch as cutekit picked up a newer ```clang``` (can't tell which one yet). Let me know if you need me to help debug.

FYI: cutekit was installed with pipx

comment.body: Yeah, itâ€™s trying to pick up the latest Clang based on the executable name alone, and it assumes clang++ is older than clang++-17 just because it lacks a number; this is a limitation. It would require a better toolchain-detection mechanism, but thatâ€™s a hard problem.

```

`./skift.sh image start` also failed

Warning: Plugin meta/plugins/__init__.py loading skipped due to: Expected cutekit version 0.9.0 but found 0.8.8

```

comment.body: There is no iso installer, you can build it as normal with `./skift.sh boot` and then take the content of `.cutekit/images/image-efi-x86_64.dir` and then  copy it to an UEFI partion

issue.title: ci: Removed unused workflows.
issue.body: Since all changes to `main` now go through the CI gate and are protected by the project lockfile, the `passing` and `stable` branches have become redundant. Every merge into `main` is already guaranteed to be tested and stable, so maintaining extra branches just duplicates CI runs and wastes resources.

comment.body: @Louciole Darwin was not removed, I just merged the two workflow files and used a matrix instead so they stay in sync.
